'''Al-Khadra Mosque''' ({{lang-ar|<big>مسجد الخضرة</big>}}, transliteration: ''Masjid al-Khadra'', translation: "the Green Mosque") also known as '''Hizn Sidna Yaq'ub Mosque''' (trans. ''Sadness of our Lord Jacob'') is a [[mosque]] situated on the lower slopes of [[Mount Gerizim]] in the southwestern quarter of the Old City of [[Nablus]] in the [[West Bank]]. The mosque is rectangular in shape, and its [[minaret]] rises {{convert|30|m|ft|sp=us}}.<ref name="Pringle_a">Pringle, 1993, pp.112.</ref>

==History==
[[File:Khadra Mosque Minaret.jpg|thumb|left|Minaret of al-Khadra Mosque, early 20th century]]

According to [[Muslim]] tradition, the mosque is situated upon the site where [[Jacob]] wept after being shown [[Joseph (Hebrew Bible)|Joseph]]'s blood-soaked tunic which suggested that he had been mauled and killed; on the right of the courtyard is a small room said to be the place where Jacob sat down and wept.<ref>Feyerick (1996) p 148</ref> Hence the mosque's alternative name "Sadness of our Lord Jacob".<ref>Luke, 1922, p.102.</ref> According to [[Samaritan]] tradition, al-Khadra Mosque had been a [[synagogue]] destroyed by the Crusaders. They claim that its [[Arabic language|Arabic]] name ''al-Khadra'' ("the Green") derived from the Samaritan ''Mahallat Khadra'' ("the place of the Green").<ref name="Pringle2"/> Archaeologist Michael Avi-Yonah identified the Khadra Mosque with the synagogue built by the Samaritan high priest Akbon in 362 CE.<ref>Avi-Yonah, Michael. [http://www.christusrex.org/www1/ofm/mad/discussion/035discuss.html Discussion: Mount Ephraim and Benjamin, 35. Neapolis - (Nablus)] Studium Biblicum Franciscum - Jerusalem. 2000-12-19.</ref>

The synagogue was rebuilt in 1137 by Ab Giluga, a Samaritan from [[Acre, Israel|Acre]]. Several Western scholars, however, believe, because of examples of [[Gothic architecture]] in portions of the present-day mosque, that in the 1170s, there stood a [[Crusade]]r church and bell tower.<ref name="Pringle2">Pringle, 1993, p.111</ref> [[Arab]] geographer [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]] records in 1225, while Nablus was under [[Ayyubid]] rule, the buildings was restored to become a Samaritan synagogue, which he referred to as "a large mosque" which the Samaritans venerated.<ref>al-Hamawi quoted in le Strange, 1890, p. [https://archive.org/stream/palestineundermo00lestuoft#page/512/mode/1up 512]</ref> It is probably from this era that the Samaritan inscriptions on a minaret wall were made.<ref>Herbermann, 1913, p.417</ref>

In 1242, however, the [[Knights Templars]] damaged the building, which was later destroyed in 1260 by the [[Mongols]].<ref>Pringle, 1993, pp.112-113.</ref> It was transformed as a mosque in 1290 by the Mamluks during the reign of [[Qalawun|Sultan Qalawun]] as attested to by a foundation inscription.<ref>Dumper, Stanley and Abu-Lughod (2007) p 266</ref> Most of the structure resembles Mamluk architecture and a ''[[mihrab]]'' was added to the mosque.<ref name="Pringle_a" />

===Second Intifada===
According to the Palestinian government and [[Gush Shalom]], during the [[Second Intifada]] in the [[Battle of Nablus]] in 2002, [[Israel]]i bulldozers destroyed 85% of the mosque, including the Mamluk-era ''mihrab''.<ref>[http://www.gush-shalom.org/terror/report1.html#nablus Report on the Destruction to Palestinian Institutions in Nablus and Other Cities (Except Ramallah) Caused by IDF Forces Between March 29 and April 21, 2002] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021023418/http://gush-shalom.org/terror/report1.html |date=October 21, 2008 }} [[Gush Shalom]]. 2002-04-22.</ref><ref>[http://www.arabicnews.com/ansub/Daily/Day/020813/2002081323.html Destruction of Nablus Old City, a war crime, Palestinian minister] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214180945/http://www.arabicnews.com/ansub/Daily/Day/020813/2002081323.html |date=2012-02-14 }} Arabic News. 2002-08-13.</ref><ref>Gresh (2004) p 171</ref> The current imam of al-Khadra Mosque, Maher Kharaz (the 'White Lion'), was removed from his position in a Palestinian Authority 'crack down' on militant imams in 1996, but was reinstated in 2006.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/876629.html Ha'aretz] 30 June 2007 Hamas preacher defies PA gov't ban on incitement in mosques By The Associated Press</ref><ref>[http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull&cid=1189411466025 Jpost]{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} 23 September 2007 Palestinian forces arrest prominent Hamas preacher</ref> Kharaz, a [[Hamas]] member and opponent of [[Fatah]], regularly defied the Fatah-led [[Palestinian National Authority]] during his weekly Friday sermons.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/29/africa/ME-GEN-Israel-Palestinians.php Hamas preacher defies government order to stop talking politics in mosques] [[International Herald Tribune]] and [[Associated Press]]. 2007-06-28.</ref> Kharaz was arrested on September 23, 2007 in another Fatah-led 'crack down' on Hamas.<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2003986679_palestinians01.html?syndication=rss Seattle Times] 1 November 2007 Abbas takes textbook approach to security By Karin Laub The Associated Press</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/nov/02/israel.comment Guardian] 2 November 2007 Fatah targets mosques in latest anti-Hamas campaign</ref><ref>[http://domino.un.org/UNISPAL.NSF/eed216406b50bf6485256ce10072f637/ac3bdabe6291fa2e8525737700711543!OpenDocument UN Doc] Chronological Review of Events Relating to the Question of Palestine, Monthly media monitoring review September 2007</ref>

