{{Orphan|date=March 2011}} {{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Rogers v. Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=September 13, |ArgueYear=2000 |DecideDate=October 26, |DecideYear=2000 |FullName=Shirley K. Rogers v. Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. |Citations=230 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/230/868/587760/ 868] |Prior=Motion to remand denied by [[United States District Court for the Western District of Tennessee|U.S. District Court for the Western District of Tennessee]], June 23, 1999 |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[Ralph B. Guy Jr.]], [[Karen Nelson Moore]], [[David Dudley Dowd Jr.|David D. Dowd, Jr.]] <small>([[United States District Court for the Northern District of Ohio|N.D. Ohio]])</small> |Majority=Dowd |JoinMajority=a unanimous court |LawsApplied={{USC|28|1441}} }}
'''''Rogers v. Wal-Mart Stores, Inc.''''', 230 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] 868 (6th Cir. 2000)<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Rogers v. Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. |vol=230 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=868 |pinpoint= |court=6th Cir. |date=2000 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/230/868/587760/ |accessdate=2017-11-08 |quote=}}</ref>, was a case decided by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|6th Circuit]] that held that [[Remand (court procedure)|remand]] to a state court cannot be achieved after [[removal jurisdiction|removal]] to a [[United States federal courts|federal court]] by lowering the [[damages]] sought to fall below the [[amount in controversy]] requirement.<ref>Yeazell, S.C. ''Civil Procedure, Seventh Edition.'' Aspen Publisher, New York, NY: 2008, p. 218</ref>
==Decision== The plaintiff sued [[Walmart]] in state court for a state law [[negligence]] action, seeking $950,000 in damages. Pursuant to [[28 U.S.C.]] § 1441<ref>{{USC|28|1441}}</ref>, the defendant removed to federal court on the basis of [[diversity jurisdiction]]. The plaintiff reduced the damages sought to less than $75,000 and petitioned for remand to state court because the amount in controversy requirement was no longer met. The 6th Circuit upheld a denial of the petition for remand, holding that the amount in controversy at the time of removal was what mattered.<ref>Yeazell, p. 218</ref>
